2	/**
3	 * @file
4	 * @brief The RRGraphView encapsulates a read-only routing resource graph as most 
5	 * clients (router, timing analyzer, etc.) only need to read a routing-resource graph (RRGraph).
6	 * 
7	 * 
8	 * The RRGraph models the FPGA's programmable routing fabric as a graph consisting of nodes and edges. 
9	 * Each node and edge is supplemented with additional metadata, such as the physical location within 
10	 * the chip and electrical properties, to optimize algorithm efficiency, aid in visualizing the chip layout, 
11	 * and estimate signal delays.
12	 * 
13	 * @par  RRGraph nodes
14	 * Each node represents a routing resource, which can be:
15	 * 1. A routing track (CHANX or CHANY).
16	 * 2. An input/output of a logic block (IPIN or OPIN).
17	 * 3. A virtual source or sink node (SOURCE or SINK).
18	 * 
19	 * @par  RRGraph edges
20	 * Each edge represents a switch between resources, which can be:
21	 * 1. A multiplexer.
22	 * 2. A tri-state buffer.
23	 * 3. A pass gate.
24	 * 4. A non-configurable buffer.
25	 * 5. A short (metal connection).
26	 * 
27	 * 
28	 * @note Despite the RRGraph containing millions of edges, there are only a few switch types.
29	 * Therefore, all switch details, including R and C, are stored using a flyweight pattern (rr_switch_inf)
30	 * rather than being directly embedded in the edge-related data of the RRGraph.
31	 * Each edge stores the ID of its associated switch for easy lookup.
32	 * 
33	 * 
34	 * \internal
35	 * A unified object that includes pointers to:
36	 * - Node storage
37	 * - TODO: Edge storage
38	 * - TODO: Node PTC storage
39	 * - TODO: Node fan-in storage
40	 * - RR node indices
41	 * \endinternal
42	
43	 *
44	 * @note The RRGraphView does not own the storage. It provides a virtual 
45	 * read-only protocol for:
46	 * - Placer
47	 * - Router
48	 * - Timing analyzer
49	 * - GUI
50	 *
51	 * Note that each client of rr_graph may get a frame view of the object
52	 * The RRGraphView is the complete frame view of the routing resource graph
53	 * - This helps to reduce the memory footprint for each client
54	 * - This avoids massive changes for each client on using the APIs
55	 *   as each frame view provides adhoc APIs for each client
56	 * \internal
57	 * TODO: More compact frame views will be created, such as:
58	 * - A mini frame view: Contains only nodes and edges, representing the 
59	 *   connectivity of the graph.
60	 * - A geometry frame view: An extended mini frame view with node-level 
61	 *   attributes, particularly geometry information (type, x, y, etc.).
62	 * \endinternal
63	 */
